<AnyLogicWorkspace WorkspaceVersion="1.9" AnyLogicVersion="8.9.8.qualifier" AlpVersion="8.9.7">
<Model>
	<Id>1744395987071</Id>
	<Name><![CDATA[Oil Terminal]]></Name>
	<Description><![CDATA[A model of a hypothetical Oil Terminal serving tankers with a berth and a railway supply. It  features AnyLogic Rail, Fluid, and Process Modeling Libraries and shows how you can efficiently combine them to simulate multi-modal facilities.
The terminal has storages for four different types of oil products: Petrol, Diesel, Fuel Oil, and Crude Oil. Each storage unit has four tanks connected to the berth and to the railway. 
The berth can serve one tanker at a time. Upon arrival, the tanker is tugged to the berth by the tugboats, connects to the pipelines, and starts loading. Each tanker has four tanks to be loaded, the product type for each tank is randomly chosen. When fully loaded, the tanker is tugged away and departs. 
A storage tank initially contains a random amount of product (but above the minimum). When the product level falls below the allowed minimum, the tank blocks its output, and the storage reorders the product to top up. The product is then delivered to the terminal by trains.
The trains have a certain lead time. They share the same track when entering and exiting, however, at the terminal, the track forks into four different tracks so that trains carrying different products can unload in parallel.
The model is fully parameterized and has a lot of different metrics as outputs so you can play with capacities, throughputs (flow rates), inventory policies, etc. to achieve optimal performance and/or resource utilization. 
]]></Description>
